# Task 1: This class will contain all the string constants for telemetry metric names and labels used in the OpenTelemetry implementation. This centralizes all metric definitions, making it easy to maintain and ensuring consistency across the codebase. Metrics, Spans, Counters, Gauges, Histograms, and their associated labels will be defined here as constants. This also allows for better organization and discoverability of all telemetry-related strings in one place. Everythibg related to telemetry metric names and labels should be defined as constants in this class, and all code that uses these metrics should reference these constants instead of hardcoding strings. This will make it easier to update metric names or labels in the future, as you will only need to change them in one place.
# Task 2: Define constants for all metric names used in the GridTopologyService, such as "grid_topology.entities_tracked" and "grid_topology.connections_tracked".
# Task 3: Add service names to the Tempo traces, right now there is only "sally" but it would be good to have more specific service names for different components (e.g. "sally.grid_topology", "sally.setpoint_service", etc.) to make it easier to filter and analyze traces in Tempo.
# Task 4: Make Loki work with the new structured logging format. This will involve updating the log format to include structured data (e.g. JSON) and ensuring that all log messages are emitted in this format. This will allow Loki to parse and index the logs more effectively, enabling powerful querying and analysis capabilities. At the moment Loki is not able to show anything because there are no labels to filter on, so adding structured logging with consistent labels will be crucial for making Loki useful for log analysis in the Sally system.
# Task 5: Update the documentation to reflect the new telemetry implementation, including how to use the constants defined in this class for metrics and spans, and how to configure the telemetry system for different services. This will help developers understand how to properly instrument their code with telemetry and ensure that they are using the correct metric names and labels for consistency across the system.
